The Government wants to limit the torture of "witches," as published in a pamphlet
Women considered witches in Burkina Faso share certain characteristics.
They usually have an advanced age, they cannot work, for example, for health reasons, they are single and have no children.
Women who "turn" witches are sent to an isolated area, so that they do not harm the rest of the village.
"Men rarely suffer such but."
"Healthy young women are also not isolated, because they help in work and have children," explains a nun who, in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso, cares in a special residence of more than a hundred women expelled from their communities.
The local government has decided to oppose this unusual "social measure."
He issued an information leaflet that should help prevent witch hunting.
However, this has a glue.
"Over 70% of adults in Burkina Faso can't read," warns the Die Standard newspaper about the downside of written awareness.
Charges of witchcraft are also common in other African countries.
In Gana, a neighbouring country in Burkina Faso, Ammy Hemmah, 72, died last week when three women and two men tortured her, covered her with gasoline and burned her.
The news appeared on the BBC.
The authors claim that it was due to a dismal accumulation of circumstances.
According to her version, the woman was placed in the oil used for ritual anointings.
It caught fire when the group wanted to "expulse the evil spirits" of women.
The isolation of "witches" is supported by people at all levels of education.
The Der Standard newspaper quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso as saying: "The devoters of human souls always posed a danger," he said.
While in Burkina Faso the government tries to appease the witch hunt, in the Gambia last year the president was still involved.
"Chambian President Jammeh, after his aunt's death, launched a wide-ranging hunt for the witches who had allegedly been linked to his death and had tried to kill the president himself through black magic."
"To help him brought shamans from nearby Guinea who, protected by police, military and the president's personal escort, forcibly took men and women randomly chosen among Gambian peoples to the president's property in Kanilai," Amnesty International says in its report.
On the farm, the people arrested had to drink a grassy one with hallucinogenic effects that also caused them intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of those arrested did not survive the stay on the estate.
After international pressure, they finally released about a thousand people in detention.
Bakala tenant: Heated up with coal stoves and signs higher rent
The elderly and reluctant man crossed the doors of the customer service center of the RPG Byty of the "coal magnate" Zdeek Bakala, the largest private owner of apartments for rent in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he had documents with the new three-storey leases: his, his, that of his daughter and that of his son, who is serving a sentence.
All three of them have just been caught up in the liberalisation of rents.
Instead of 3,500 Czech kronor a month, the son will pay 4,100 kronor from next year for a two-storey flat with a second-class separate kitchen.
"In addition, it does not have hot water and the heating is based on a solid fuel boiler," the man shows with his finger in his son's new contract, on whose signature he has full powers.
"But I signed it," he explains half angrily, half resigned.
The civil association BytyOKD.cz, which described the new rental conditions as "incorrect and indecent," recommends that tenants not sign the new contracts and wait until December 7, when it will publish a guide informing how to proceed in these cases.
But, in the face of this, man only makes one gesture.
"Everybody says one thing," he says with a bad face.
Ostrava is becoming a major liberalisation testing laboratory.
After New Year, it will occur with the vast majority of the apartments that, in the Czech Republic, have so far been under regulated rent.
That's why Aktuáln.cz decided to visit the "laboratory" in person.
RPG's mining waiting room is one of four in Ostrava and, at nine, on Tuesday, it was already full.
Right next to the doors are the security guards and next to you a machine to pick up numbers.
"Rental 2011" can be read on a light button on your touch screen.
