The architects have understood that the offices also need childcare
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
No one would say that he also hides inside a small nursery with everything in such facilities: colored walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, the children of Arch.Design's employees can go to her.
The architectural project company Arch.Design, from whose studio numerous known buildings from Brno came, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its miniguard.
About 90 people work at the company, mainly in the baby boom age, and wanted to allow architects and broadcasters to return to work soon after motherhood.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, nursery is one of the benefits offered by Arch.Design to its workers as part of its social program.
Construction companies and architects in this way have the possibility to combine a demanding profession with childcare.
The miniguarding was an idea of Arch's own employees.Designu and, with the support of the management, managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company's miniguarding is financed through the European Social Fund under the Operational Programme on Human Resources and Employment, as well as the State budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the funding granted (a staff of more than CZK 2.8 million) were able to buy the equipment and, after two years, hire qualified staff and services.
When it exhausts the financing (two years), the company Arch.Design has an obligation to keep the miniguarding in operation with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and the financing application was submitted by Economy Rating.
The care of children is in the hands of qualified staff; in addition, a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education are present all day for her care. The nursery currently accommodates children without age limits, although most of them are under three.
Since this is a "miniguardian," it can only simultaneously accommodate up to five children, although with shifts they go more during the day.
The operation of the nursery is flexible to adapt to the needs of parents and children of all workers have the same right to use childcare, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although it is individual education and care, the contents of the miniguarding programme are comparable to the regular preschool curriculum.
In it, children not only play, but also receive quality teaching: from basic learning to school preparation, they teach to English.
The class not only has toys and board games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go to see their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up children late from school when they are away from their workplace.
Thus, parents are more productive while working.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a loyalty relationship between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is among the companies that sign that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program reinforced the marketing of staff.
The house of the bones continues to fascinate after 100 years. Watch Gaudí's interiors
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs reminiscent of the column of a dinosaur and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Due to her shape similar to a skeleton, the locals nicknamed her "the house of the bones."
Its organic forms, its striking colors, the novel use of the stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade reminiscent of the scales and the ubiquitous gently curved lines, all this is typical of the secession of Antoni Gaudí.
The cover of the house plays with dreamy lines, delicate colors and textures taken from nature and fauna.
Reading more attention, you see a certain geometry, rhythm and carefully thought-out order.
In the evening, the whole facade of the house seems even more impressive, as it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Serpent and the torsion of forms continues to surprise us also within it.
The undulating wood copies the frames of the windows, the railings, the door ornaments, the mirains and the signs.
Casa Batlló, which is located in the neighborhood of Eixample at number 43 of the lively shopping street of Passeig de Grácia, emerged from the remodeling of a house of 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on tearing down the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea of carrying out a novel and cheaper reconstruction.
However, Casa Batlló, formed by various apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
The architect Josep María Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in its plans of the project, ornaments for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the mosaics used on the facade emerged.
On the facade other creators and artists also work.
The collaboration in the proposals of the Batlló House was the beginning of Jujol's successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of Casa Milá and the park Guell de Gaudí, in which other pieces of the same are located.
Due to her organic shape, the locals shortly after its completion nicknamed her "the house of the bones."
Others, due to the specific window opening mechanism, began calling it "the yawn house."
It is also said that, at the top of the construction, the sword of San Jorge, patron saint of Catalonia, appears.
Other sculptural elements of the construction hide religious motives.
Gaudí projected in the house a unique system for the central heating season with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
Your tilt of forty-five degrees may be strange.
During the construction, Gaudí did not respect the rules of construction of the moment at all and did not be influenced by them.
Even so, the construction obtained the corresponding permit from the beginning, although obviously in it the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the city council was so shocked by the result that it requested that it be corrected.
It was upset, for example, that construction included columns even to the public sidewalk.
The arrangements were never made, on the contrary: just fifteen days after the city council's request, Josep Batlló applied (and obtained) permission to rent the two tallest floors of the building.
On the lower floors the owner himself settled.
In the second-floor gallery was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The six-storey house is completely crossed by a staircase leading to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the living rooms and a larger group can communicate in this way without problems, without giving up the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with Gaudí's reconstruction, not only got a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with the light, white and blue tiles covering the inner courtyard and skylights.
The game with the two colors brings the maximum light on all the floors of the house.
It was based simply on the principle that white reflects more light than the dark colors, which instead absorb the sun rays.
Anyone can visit the Casa Batlló, which in 2005 was added to Unesco's World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and most recharged apartment of those accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that this is a very beneficial business and expanded visits to the common area and the attic, including the roof terrace.
The price of entry to the monument is not negligible, reaching 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and tourist card holders get 20% discount.
The amount significantly exceeds the price of the entrance of Gaudí's other constructions in the city.
