Still, that he can turn it into a successful campaign for a second term in next year's election will depend on whether the clearly affected Mrs Fernandez puts aside the intransigence of her late husband, her predecessor and political partner, Néstor Kirchner.
And, at this point, the indications are inconclusive.
Mr Kirchner, who continued to take over economic policy even after his wife succeeded him as chairman, was in the habit of drawing up budgets that underestimated tax revenues, economic growth and inflation.
This allowed the presidential marriage to spend the extra income at its discretion.
In theory, Ms. Fernandez's government lost its majority in Congress last year.
However, the opposition is divided, a situation that has worsened following Kirchner's death from a heart attack on October 27.
Some dissenting members of the Peronist movement in power have clashed with Ms Fernandez.
However, after chaotic sessions in which one deputy punched another in the face and other deputies accused the government of bribery, Congress decided to reject the 2011 budget.
"I'm not going to argue," the president said.
The 2010 budget will therefore apply to next year, which will give the president an even greater scope for action when it comes to spending it.
The economy is improving considerably: it is likely to grow to 9% this year.
The official inflation rate is currently 11.1 per cent, but numerous private calculations, in addition to the wage requirements of trade unions, put it at about 30 per cent.
Mr Kirchner, who took power in 2003 when Argentina was on the brink of economic collapse, made growth and poverty reduction his priorities, rather than control of inflation.
He refused to negotiate with the IMF, pressured the private sector and had INDEC, the statistics institute, adapt official inflation statistics.
Will President Fernández now dictate these policies?
He has convened meetings between the private sector and union leaders.
In addition, officials say they want to limit wage increases next year to 18 per cent.
The economy has been driven by high prices for Argentine agricultural exports in the world.
However, inflation has limited the momentum to growth achieved with a major devaluation in 2002.
Perhaps for this reason, Ms Fernandez is signalling her wanting to restore Argentina's financial ties to the rest of the world.
Earlier in the year, the government reached an agreement with bondholders who had refused a previous forced restructuring of the debt that Argentina had not paid in 2001.
At present, it appears that Ms Fernandez is about to conclude an agreement with the creditor governments grouped with the Paris Club, to which she owes about $6.7 billion.
The Kirchners always insisted that this would not involve IMF supervision, as is customary.
Last month, however, Amado Boudou, the Minister of Economy, announced that the Fund will offer "technical assistance" to develop a new price index for national consumption, which seems to be the prelude to the clean-up of INDEC.
It is unclear whether President Fernandez wants to remain in politics when her term ends, given that she no longer has her husband by her side.
If he does, he will need to win the support of the middle class, much of which has grown tired of Kirchnerism.
When the Argentines return from their summer holiday in March, the wave of sympathy for her will have fallen.
If she wants to win other elections, she will have to decide whether or not she repudiates, calmly, many of her husband's policies.
