Grammy Awards nominations: Michael Daugherty and Steve Mackey in best classic album direction
Nominations in the field of classical music for the 53rd edition of the Grammy Awards include a mix of musicians and composers from around the world.
The main nominations were for Michael Daugherty for "Deus Ex Machina," by piano and orchestra, of five movements, and Steve Mackey with "Dreamhouse," an eclectic orchestra work of three movements.
Among the nominees with ties to Southern California are Estonian composer Arvo P.rt for his symphony No 4, "Los Angeles," a piece commissioned by the Los Angeles Philharmonic and premiered at Walt Disney Concert Hall in 2009.
Los Angeles-based composer Avner Dorman is also nominated for his Mandolin Concerto.
The nominations for classical music are distributed in thirteen categories covering orchestra albums, opera, choral and solo.
The classic producer category of the year includes five nominees: Blanton Alspaugh, David Frost, Tim Handley, Marina and Victor Ledin, and James Mallinson.
The nominees for the classical music album are Bruckner for the Symphonies No 3 and No 4 of the Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra; Daugherty for "Deus Ex Machina" and "Metropolis Symphony" of the Nashville Symphony Orchestra; Steven Mackey for "Dreamhouse" of the Boston Modern Orchestra Project and Synergy Vocals; "Sacrificium - the Art of the Castrati" by several artists; and the "Requiem" of Verdi of ChicagoSymphony Orchestra and Chorus.
In the opera category, the nominees are Berg for "Lulu" of the Royal Opera House orchestra; Adolf Hasse for "Marc Antonio e Cleopatra" by Ars Lyrica Houston; Kaija Saariaho for "L'Amour de Loin" by the Deutsches Symphonie-Orchester Berlin; Rodion Shchedrin for "The Enchanted Wanderer" by the orchestra and choir of the Mariinsky Theatre; and Arthur Sullivan for "Ivanhoe" by the BBC National Orchesof Wales.
Songwriters nominated for a Grammy for contemporary compositions include P.rt for Symphony No 4, Daugherty for "Deus Ex Machina," Hans Werner Henze for "Appassionately Plus," Magnus Lindberg for "Graffiti" and Shchedrin for "The Enchanted Wanderer."
Symphony No. 4 of P.t. premiered at Disney Hall in January 2009 in a session recorded by the Los Angeles Philharmonic, directed by Esa-Pekka Salonen.
The roughly 30-minute piece is nicknamed "Los Angeles" and is dedicated to former oil tycoon Mikhail Khodorkovsky, imprisoned in Russia.
Dorman's "Mandolin Concerto" is nominated for instrumental solo performance with orchestra.
The Los Angeles composer wrote the 15-minute piece specifically for the mandolin Avi Avital, who performed the concert with the New York-based Metropolis Ensemble.
"It composed it with sounds from the Middle East and numerous scales and rhythms of North Africa," Dorman said in a telephone interview.
Director Pierre Boulez, 85, was nominated in the orchestra function category, for directing the Chicago Symphony Orchestra during a recording of Stravinsky's works.
Among the instrumental soloists nominated are pianists Nelson Freire and Marc-André Hamelin; organist Paul Jacobs; violinist Julia Fischer; and harpist Sarah Schuster Ericsson.
The nominees as vocal soloists are all women this year: Anne Sofie Von Otter, Cecilia Bartoli, Lucia Duchonová, Vivica Genaux and Measha Brueggergoman.
In the classic mixing category, soprano Jessye Norman was nominated for her recording of "Roots - My Life, My Song."
