An arsenic-resistant microbe raises the possibility of new ways of life on Earth... or elsewhere
The discovery of a strange bacteria that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients expands the possibility of finding new ways of life on Earth and possibly on other planets.
Although the researchers discovered the curious bacteria here on Earth, they say it shows that there may be life forms without the main elements they considered essential.
"This organism has a double capacity."
"It can grow either with phosphorus or arsenic."
"That makes it very peculiar, although it lacks little to be a really 'alienient' kind of way of life," Paul C said. W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of the report, which appears in Thursday's online edition of the journal Science.
For a long time, there have been six major essential elements for life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulphur.
However, researchers have discovered that the bacteria, found in Mono Lake, California, may continue to grow after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
"It makes you think about how much is possible," said Ariel D. Anbar from Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
According to Anbar, the finding is important for the search for life on planets other than Earth, since researchers need to be able to recognize life, know what it looks like.
The study focuses on a microbe discovered on Earth.
However, the convening of a press conference to discuss it, at which no details of the discovery were disseminated, generated great speculation on the Internet about the possibility that the report indicated the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
He didn't do it.
What the discovery "yes shows is that in other planetary environments, there could be organisms that use other elements to boost their biochemistry and that the set of "standard" elements that we consider indispensable to life may not be so fixed," said Charles Cockell, professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, in Milton Keynes, United Kingdom.
Cockell was not part of the investigation team.
"This work is novel because it demonstrates the replacement of one element with another in biochemistry and basic biochemical structure," Cockell added.
The discovery was not made by chance.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's astrobiology institute, which led the study, focused on Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are similar from a chemical point of view, so he speculated that a microbe exposed to both could replace each other.
"Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is similar to that of phosphorus."
"Therefore, it may be difficult for organisms to differentiate them."
"However, arsenic is different enough that it doesn't work as well as phosphorus, so it comes in and, to put it in some way, it appeals to biochemical machinery," explains Anbar.
The researchers collected the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed them to increasing concentrations of arsenic, which they managed to adapt and used to grow.
The microbe grows better with phosphorus, but the fact that it can show that it can live with arsenic in its place raises the possibility that there may be a natural existence of arsenic-using form of life, either in other areas of the Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
- Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said the idea that arsenic could be replaced with phosphorus is not new, but no one example had been found to show that it works.
Arsenic was more common in the early ages of Earth, he said, so researchers speculated that the first life forms may have used it.
"Yes, it suggests that there could be other means of generating life, not just the way life was formed on Earth in the past," said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health.
