Lion ready to roar again, while MGM restructuring gets final court approval
After 18 months of turmoil and uncertainty, MGM has finally got the green light to start over.
On Thursday, a federal bankruptcy judge in New York officially approved the "pre-prerogated" plan by creditors to wipe out about $5 billion in debt, paving the way for the 86-year-old entertainment company to focus its efforts on the production and premiere of films and television shows.
Thursday's ruling confirms that the plan meets the demands of the U.S. bankruptcy code, so there are no other legal hurdles for MGM to relaunch under Spyglass Entertainment founders Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, who will become the chief executives of what will be a reduced study.
Staff will be reduced from 400 to approximately 320.
In fact, MGM won't be leaving Chapter 11 until JPMorgan Chase closes a planned $500 million credit facility to fund the operations and productions of the new MGM.
The investment bank is currently syndicating the credit, which on its own is contributing $75 million, and is expected to be funded in mid-December.
The restructuring process of the study began in May 2009, when investment bank Moelis and Co. was hired to provide advice on the management needed to order its finances, as it struggled to make interest payments of $300 million a year.
In August, director Harry Sloan was replaced by Stephen Cooper, a former Enron chairman and bankrupt business recovery expert, known for his work at Krispy Kreme Doughnuts.
Moelis and Cooper's attempts to resolve MGM's financial tribulations and satisfy the studio's more than 140 creditors took much longer than expected.
After several months of discussions, in late 2009 the parties agreed to put the company up for sale.
However, the auction attracted few bidders and none willing to pay the more than $2 billion the creditors sought.
Before spring this year, he returned to the design table as the MGM team began working on a restructuring plan that, after months of debate and internal disagreements, was eventually backed by creditors in late October.
When MGM officially emerges from bankruptcy in the coming weeks, Moelis and Cooper's companies will receive multimillion-dollar bonuses for their work.
Moelis and Co., which has already received $1.2 million, will get a $9.5 million payment.
Cooper's companies, which have been raising $375,000 a month for their company management services, will receive a $4 million "successful honorary."
Barber and Birnbaum plan to resume production at MGM, which premiered only one film this year, and collected an annual slate of seven or eight films that will be released in 2012.
They also plan to co-finance two films based on "The Hobbit," along with Warner Bros.
The studio needs to arrange a separate loan of between $265 million and $275 million to fund its share of the two films, which will be directed by Peter Jackson.
Investor Carl Icahn, who owns about 18 per cent of MGM's debt, had been trying to fix a merger of the studio with Lions Gate Entertainment, in which he is the largest shareholder.
However, recent talks between the two companies did not result in a deal.
