As an urban sergeant, Tang Shenbin marked the passage in a city square, severely inspecting the nervous people in his care, issuing orders quietly with military authority.
He wanted the female members of chengguan, the corpulent police of the urban order of China, feared and despised for their whimsical strong measures and their inclination to violence, to communicate a certain impression to a handful of spectators.
"Firms".
"Attention".
"Show them," he whispered, "How are the pretty girls?"
Four girls who barely spent their teens wearing white gloves and identical olive green jackets and tight trousers to get attention.
Four pairs of perfectly aligned black shoes.
Four elegant hats placed perfectly on top of hair tied with blue and white striped buns.
"Personally, I think they look normal," Mr. Tang, contemptuously.
"The models are cute".
More than one government has tried to clean up the image of China's urban inspectors.
One city ordered all new recruits to have a grade title.
Guangdong Province changed the greyish green color of the uniforms to a supposedly more attractive blue.
Wuhan, in central China, replaced the use of force with intimidating glances: in 2009, according to a report, 50 officers surrounded a deciquatic snacks cart, and watched it with a frown constantly frowned for half an hour, until the street vendor picked up his stuff and left.
Xindu, an urban district of 680,000 in Chengdu, has chosen a radical makeover.
Since 2003, the district has added 13 women to its urban police, expressly chosen for their appearance, proportion and youth.
The idea is to give the rough cop a softer, more feminine side.
Unfortunately, even Scarlett Johansson would have to fight to increase China's tiny respect for these city squads.
And for good reason, critics would argue.
Unlike the police, these officers are only authorized to enforce city ordinances, imposing fines and other administrative penalties.
But the Chinese news media routinely portray a different reality.
In January 2008, inspectors from Hubei Province beat down a passerby after using his cellphone to film them while they were dissolving a protest against a waste dump.
Last year, a training manual for inspectors in Beijing was stolen and posted on the Internet, describing how effectively whipping criminals without making them bleed.
Earlier this year, a Shanghai watermelon street vendor suffered brain damage after a scuffle with five officers.
A video game full of violence, available to download online, features Chinese-trained inspectors attacking street vendors.
"Chengguan has left a scar on government," lamented China Daily, a national publication, last year after another controversy over tactics.
The newspaper demanded "a really meticulous clean-up."
Skeptics say the current approach is far from this.
After the district requested eight new female recruits in October through a notice, an editorial in The Beijing Evening News asked whether women had real duties or were simply a stage distraction.
The answer seems to be a little bit of both.
The district's warning called for female candidates aged 18 to 22, with a good figure "and the five harmonious facial features."
They should have above average height, more than 1.6 meters or 5 feet, 2 1/2 inches.
Retirement at the age of 26 is mandatory.
Officials said the work was physically too arduous for women over 25 years of age.
"His image is the important thing," an anonymous district official told Rednet.com, a quasi-government website.
"First, the external qualities of the candidates will determine whether they meet the requirements, such as height, weight, facial features, etc."
Then comes the temperament "and the inner qualities."
Female chengguan are like vases, she said, adding, "in addition to being vases, they will have other responsibilities."
Zheng Lihua, deputy director of the district city's administration office, is not eager to back up that description.
But he noted that height demands were standard in many Chinese job warnings for both sexes.
Then comes the demand for harmonious facial features.
If this means being handsome, it's a matter of debate among the Chinese.
Surely the disabled or disfigured should not be presented.
"We cannot allow a cook or a hunchback person to come to work here," Mr Zheng said.
"His image wouldn't be right".
Liu Yi, who patrols Baoguang Square near a monastery, is 22 years old, with his cheeks and subtly curved mouth.
She doesn't think the accent on her appearance is sexist, she said.
"Do you think I look sexy in this uniform?" he asked with a sardonic look.
