Can civility build a bridge to unite divisions?
After a remarkable campaign for invective and negativity, this week has sparked some civility in Washington.
Is it a harbinger of genuine bipartisan future cooperation or an illusory moment before a quick return to partisan combat in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders did not produce any progress on the big issues to be addressed during the outgoing session.
But from what everyone says, it was at least a polite discussion about the differences of the two sides, as well as a recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than being another empty episode to earn partisan points.
Wednesday's public meeting of the president's deficit committee was equally civilised, despite the remaining political differences between members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months generated mutual respect that transcends the ideological divide that still separates members.
That's hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has come.
Both sides are now in a probationary period, probing each other to identify signs of cooperativism and commitment, as they try to assess the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters for a renewed partisan war.
Reason why Tuesday's meeting and subsequent evaluations of it by participants were made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and are too deeply rooted to suggest any rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it's taxes, expenses, healthcare or social assistance, the two sides are at opposite poles.
Still, the November election has softened the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
"There's no doubt that things have changed with regard to the way things are said," said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
"They are inevitable after the election.
Elections arouse party passions, which are then extinguished.
That's good".
On some issues, particularly those on the agenda of the outgoing session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax cuts expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of this.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all reductions, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, there is likely to be a compromise to expand unemployment benefits, probably because Republicans can't make them believe they favor tax cuts for the wealthy, denying unemployment benefits for unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, there is greater optimism about a possible deal on these issues during the outgoing session, along with the ratification of the new START (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty) pact.
But William Galston, of the Brookings Institution, warns that successful cooperation on pressing issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to continued bipartisanship when the new 112th. Congress meets Jan.
Instead, he said that it is very likely and even inevitable that a period of disagreement will begin.
"After the things that need to be done are carried out, in the short term psychology will reverse the situation to one of confrontation," he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that civility can lead to true cooperation.
"I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as a rehearsal for the main event of 2012," he said.
The reasons have much to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and Tea Party voters, who contributed decisively to its creation.
As aware as Republican leaders have about the dangers of exaggerating their position, they know they must try to keep their promises to cut state spending and override the new health care law.
These party lines are already clearly seen in the initial reactions to the deficit commission's recommendations, which include reforming the tax code and raising some taxes and the retirement age, and cutting spending.
Co-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken care of one of the toughest jobs in Washington and, according to their own assessment, have forcibly introduced the deficit issue to the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member commission to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and have been struggling to get close to that figure.
The greatest resistance is among the elected officials on the panel, suggesting that in fiscal matters there are, at least now, few bases or desire for compromise.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between White House Republicans and those of Congress.
The first will happen next year in the form of party clashes, when Republicans challenge Obama on the budget, taxes and health care, followed by a period of heightened bipartisan cooperation.
What would change bring about?
The public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a stalemate, as happened in 1995, then both parties will watch the reaction of people carefully.
Whoever they think is losing is likely to change course and seek compromise.
However, this may be an optimistic vision.
Partisanship and polarization are now greater than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a bigger ideological gap between Obama and congressional Republicans than there was between President Bill Clinton and Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as the mere prelude to a more momentous election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilism shown this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort from both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
