The second is the recovery of the framework, although now it seems like science fiction, with a very favorable stream of opinion, close to 50% of the population.
The third, a redesign of the euro, in line with the German proposals of greater macroeconomic control, budgetary rigour, fines to the transgressive countries, possible suspensions of payments of some of them and extension to the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and has been defining for a long time, so now there are no excuses.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission were stimulating deficits, the German government pulled out of its sleeve a constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of divergence between what Germany believed should be made (plans of fiscal rigour and stability in public finances), and what its European partners, including France, were practicing.
The second on the front was given by the Central European country when Merkel painfully extended Greece's rescue decision.
Already then it was the subject of fierce criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public opinion and the published one were very much against Greece's bailout.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel again emerges with a clear position, demanding the reform of the Union's treaties, in order to make it possible to rescue a country and, at the same time, force private lenders to bear some of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, as it has precipitated the Irish crisis and everything else.
