Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
And he is telling us all that, although measures must now be taken with which he may not agree very much, from that date the old operation of the euro will have been completed.
2013 will mean the birth of a new monetary area, in which the infringing countries will be severely punished, they can be forced to declare themselves in suspension of payments and, in that case, the private sector will also bear some of the cost.
Germany is pointing out to us that we must follow a severe growth path with high rates of savings and investment, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
Another alternative based on debt and construction, with huge holes in the balance of payments, such as the one that has presided over Spanish growth in the boom years, simply will not tolerate it.
The envy is clear.
And we would do wrong not to understand.
It is not just a question of redirecting the public deficit to 3% in 2013.
What they demand of us is much harder.
And the worst thing we could do in these circumstances is to deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will give way to greater tranquillity.
And let's take advantage of the window of opportunity they have given us, until spring 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero has also understood this and his double manifesto (the reforms promised after last Saturday's meeting with big companies and yesterday's announcement of new measures) suggests that, despite criticism of Merkel, the thesis has been opened that order must be put at home.
But the red line Germany has drawn there is, and it doesn't look like they're going to move it.
And, among the possibilities envisaged, that of leaving a monetary area too crowded from unserious countries, it cannot be excluded.
Then Germany will always be able to tell us that it had already warned us.
Sport and fraud of law
Trees like those of Alonso and Ramos before the Ajax show wit but no will to escape a sanction.
The expulsion allegedly devised by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the match played on 23 November against Ajax in the Champions League has caused rivers of ink to be written about whether or not such behaviour is unsportsmanlike and whether, eventually, both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, within a few minutes to finish the game (which their team already clearly had won), the two players deliberately lost time when it came to taking faults to cause the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid will already finish as leader of their group, both players will serve the regulatory sanction the next league match, against the Auxerre, and will be able to pass clean cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA disciplinary committee has sanctioned the team's coach, José Mourinho, with two games, and the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or the like is not a new practice, but rather frequent in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, of the unwritten rules, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate that arose in the reported case is due to the fact that it has been starred by a team of the entity of Real Madrid (which in its anthem boasts of nobility and honor, and that in past times it has fined its players for similar acts) and the orchestrated dramatization, apparently, by Mourinho, who adds one more episode to his long history of histrionic and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this type of behaviour not expressly prohibited by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, that is, if these actions commit fraud of law; since, in fact, they are actions that respect the sports regulations, but seem to avoid their meaning.
The question involves examining the kind of damage they cause to the sporting spirit.
One of the assets that understands the sporting spirit is the physical integrity of opposing players, an aspect that with these actions was not endangered, that is, there was no violent game.
Another of these assets referred to with fair play is to prevent the team of the offending players from taking unfair advantage of the opposing team, which did not happen either.
However, the paradoxical thing about the action of the Real Madrid players is that it did not conform to what we normally characterize as cheating or fraud of law, because their violation of the rules was not done in secret to try to avoid the sanction, but precisely their action tried to be the most evident in order to receive the punishment of the referee.
They waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage offenders get in the intentional misdemeanour examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that the rival is not disadvantaged or profited in the same match, because obviously the result of the action means leaving the team itself with fewer players.
And it's not a useful strategy for the next game either, as the club won't be able to count on those players.
The advantage, obviously, is that the players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that can threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, as the team can be eliminated at the first change, and in addition with this performance the players fulfill a penalty match and move on to the second cycle of cards, in which the suspension for card accumulation occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So, if you go rounds, it's not so clear it's an advantage.
Ultimately, these actions do not go against the sporting spirit, of which it is part of to make strategic decisions that favor to make the most of what the rules allow.
In the case at hand, the players did not act to evade the application of the sanction (this would be a clear case of fraud of law), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without overcoming the punishment or fleeing it.
Although the border between ingenuity and law fraud is diffuse, on this occasion I think it was a clear case of ingenuity.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises by two factors: because it was two self-expulsions and the way in which the transmission of the guideline was carried out to provoke them.
The damage caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not as ethical as it is aesthetic.
