U.S. changes rules to get visa
Persons must go to the Visa Applicant Service Centres before their interview in the Consular Section; the cost will be lower and the waiting time.
From January 10, 2011, the procedure of processing a visa will be changed at the U.S. Embassy and consulates.
Under the new procedure, most applicants will have to go to the Visa Applicant Service Centres (ASC) before their interview in the Consular Section.
ASC staff will take the applicant's biometric information, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for applicants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to arrange the appointment, another payment to process the visa application and another for the courier service to deliver the document.
The applicant will only make a single payment that will cover the three services.
The current rate will remain unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for petitioned visa cases (including temporary worker visas) and $390 for merchant visas and investors.
People who wish to renew their visa will not have to go to an interview with the Consular Officer, but will only go to the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and take their fingerprints.
Because biometric information will be taken from the ASC, applicants requiring a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain in the Consular Section less time than in the past.
Likewise, those applying for a visa in the Consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of $26.
For additional information on the new visa application procedure, please visit the following page http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201.Visas-FAQs.html
