Climate: France's sloppiness on its funding pledges
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine whether the rapidly unblocked funding pledges (called fast starts or early) by developed countries have been respected.
And the French saucepans have been unveiled.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries committed themselves to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union committed itself to EUR 7.2 billion over three years and France EUR 1.260 million (i.e. 420 million per year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU has put on the table its best letters to convince its partners that its commitment to fast-thart funding is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press conference, a major complementary event, the distribution of brochures...
The transparency operation was appreciable and appreciated for what was really worth it: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released 2.2 billion euros, which puts it on track to meet its commitment of 7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
Under the Copenhagen Agreement, the money must be "new and additional" to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without harming official development assistance.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what "new and additional" means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
At present, everyone chooses the reference that suits him best.
For example, the European Commission has taken as its reference in 2009: international funding is maintained and 150 million in three years in fast-start financing is added.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of the year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers that the financing of "all new projects" of 2010 is "new and additional."
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of previous years or to the total level of official development assistance.
In particular, the total amount of aid from France to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease), while it seeks to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funds..."
Another crucial element, the distribution between donations and loans.
Again, there is no standard and each one chooses the calculation method.
Some, like France, consider that each euro borrowed is equivalent to a euro donated.
Obviously, such a thing is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often, projects related to emission reduction that are based on more effective technologies), it is impossible to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is donated... At most, only the cost of the loan for the loan for the country granting the loan (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate) should be computed for your commitments.
But France does not find such reasoning useful: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euros); consult the EU document to see it by your own eyes.
This is the only country in the Union that uses the loan so frequently.
Germany uses it by 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect its commitments to 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union contributes a euro to fulfil its commitment, France only contributes ten cents and considers the effort to be comparable.
A good trick.
In short, in its fast-start funding, France carries out a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to actions over time and, on the other, in relation to the real financial effort.
Spending only 36.1 million euros, he manages to give the impression that he spends 420 million "new and additional," as promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who has dealt with arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States go to continue to donate when they can simply lend?) and in the negotiations, since developing countries are not fools...
The chapter on early funding is a relatively short-term minutiae in relation to the whole climate negotiations.
But it could be a grain of extra sand in the immense machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope it doesn't.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
But, in particular, France could advance the discussions on betting on long-term funding (another essential chapter currently under discussion): we will not get rid of the question of the "additional character" or the method of computing loans.
France could change its stance to become as progressive on this issue as it is with others.
We therefore hope for the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast starts and its vision of the "additional nature" and the use of loans would help improve the level of international confidence needed to move forward with negotiations.
